eam18=[[Dunedin Blue Jays]]|league18=[[Florida State League]]|manager18=[[Denis Menke]]\n|level19=[[Class A-Short Season|A-Short Season]]|team19=[[Utica Blue Jays]]|league19=[[New York\u2013Penn League]]|manager19=[[Duane Larson]]\n|level20=[[Rookie League|Rookie]]|team20=[[Medicine Hat Blue Jays]]|league20=[[Pioneer League (baseball)|Pioneer League]]|manager20=[[John McLaren (baseball)|John McLaren]]}}<ref>Johnson, Lloyd, and Wolff, Miles, ed., ''The Encyclopedia of Minor League Baseball'', 2nd and 3rd editions. Durham, North Carolina: Baseball America, 1997 and 2007</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n*[https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/TOR/1978.shtml 1978 Toronto Blue Jays team page] at Baseball Reference\n*[http://baseball-almanac.com/teamstats/roster.php?y=1978&t=TOR 1978 Toronto Blue Jays team page] at www.baseball-almanac.com\n\n{{1978 MLB season by team}}\n{{Toronto Blue Jays}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n | title = 1978 Toronto Blue Jays Season\n | years = 1978\n | before = [[1977 Toronto Blue Jays season]]\n | after = [[1979 Toronto Blue Jays season]]\n}}\n{{end}}\n\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays seasons]]\n[[Category:1978 Major League Baseball season|Toronto Blue Jays season]]\n[[Category:1978 in Canadian sports]]\n[[Category:1978 in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1978_Toronto_Blue_Jays_season"}
{"title_page": "Ray Trew", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name= Ray Trew\n|image=\n|caption=\n|image_size=\n|birth_name=Ray Trew\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=[[England]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|occupation=[[Businessperson|Businessman]]\n|known= Owner of<br />''Contracting Solutions Group'' \n|spouse = \n|children=\n}}\n'''Raymond Arthur Trew''' (born December 1954)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/h8xK01UWHMbkqW_DxKzFZWVIBzo/appointments|title=Raymond Arthur TREW - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> is a [[Businessperson|businessman]] and former football club [[Chairman (official)|chairman]] from [[Lincolnshire]]. He is a former board member of [[Lincoln City F.C.]], [[Notts County F.C.]], and [[Notts County Ladies F.C.]].\n\nTrew achieved his wealth through [[recruitment]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/paulfletcher/2010/12/can_paul_ince_cut_it_at_notts.html#279512|title=Can Paul Ince cut it at Notts County?|author=Paul Fletcher|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 December 2010|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref> having founded Contracting Solutions Group in 1995.<ref name=lorien>{{cite web|url=http://www.lorienresourcing.co.uk/about-us/management/6-ray-trew/default.aspx|title=the team: Ray Trew|publisher=Lorien Resourcing|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref> The company posted a \u00a33.7m profit in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/fasttrack/leagues/dbDetails.asp?siteID=5&compID=2967&yr=2010|title=Rank: 124   Contracting Solutions Group|publisher=Fasttrack|accessdate=18 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316172751/http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/fasttrack/leagues/dbDetails.asp?siteID=5&compID=2967&yr=2010|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Trew also maintains numerous other [[Privately held company|private companies]],<ref name=\":0\" /> though in 2019 his application for a gangmaster's license was turned down on the grounds that his previous business conduct was not 'fit and proper'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/news/local-news/former-notts-county-owner-ray-3077195|title=Ex-Notts owner Ray Trew's conduct 'extremely concerning' as he is denied licence|last=Whitfield|first=David|date=2019-07-10|website=nottinghampost|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/news/local-news/former-imps-director-refused-licence-3076882|title=Former Imps director labelled 'not fit and proper' by officials|last=Hennessy|first=Peter|date=2019-07-10|website=lincolnshirelive|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Lincoln City==\nOn 5 August 2003, Trew became an Associate Director at [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10440~406690,00.html\n|title=New Associate Director Comes On Board\n|date=5 August 2003\n|publisher=Lincoln City F.C. Official Website\n|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> becoming a full director at the end of the month.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10440~416709,00.html\n|title=Ray Becomes A 'Trew' Director\n|date=27 August 2003\n|publisher=Lincoln City F.C. Official Website\n|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> In August 2005 he was appointed Chairman of Football with Steff Wright succeeding Rob Bradley as Chairman of the Board.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10440~752929,00.html\n|title=Former Chairman Played \"A Massive Part\"\n|date=9 December 2005\n|publisher=Lincoln City F.C. Official Website\n|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> He departed in January 2006 after a boardroom dispute which saw manager [[Keith Alexander (footballer)|Keith Alexander]] placed on gardening leave, then re-instated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2330675/Lincolns-version-of-Big-Brother-starts-to-spin-out-of-control.html|title=Lincoln's version of Big Brother starts to spin out of control|publisher=The Telegraph|date=16 January 2006|accessdate=18 January 2011|author=Simon Goodley|location=London}}</ref> In April three of Trew's companies then terminated their sponsorship deals with the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/lincolnshire/4921702.stm|title=Imps on lookout for new sponsors |publisher=BBC|date=19 April 2006|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent bid to buy the club and provide substantial investment was blocked by the Lincoln City board, with chairman Steff Wright publicly questioning Trew's motives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twohundredpercent.net/?p=4500|title=The morning after the night before|publisher=Two hundred percent|date=11 February 2010|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/lincoln_city/5238016.stm|title=Lincoln chairman wary of takeover|publisher=BBC|date=2 August 2006|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Lincoln Ladies==\nIn 2006 Trew joined the committee of [[Lincoln Ladies F.C.|Lincoln City Ladies]]. In addition to an \u00a38,000-per-season sponsorship through his SportsTV company, Trew provided additional backing of up to \u00a310,000 to aid the club's promotion bid.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/nov/06/womensfootball.sport|title=Lincoln's original imps still set for the top despite cup defeat|author=Tony Leighton|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 November 2006|accessdate=18 January 2011|location=London}}</ref> In 2008 the club changed its name to OOH Lincoln Ladies, due to a sponsorship deal with Trew's Out Of Home marketing company.<ref name=ooh>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/nov/30/lincoln-women-football-super-league|title=OOH Lincoln declare intention to join women's Super League in 2011|author=Tony Leighton|publisher=The Guardian|date=30 November 2009|accessdate=18 January 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nTrew also backed the club's successful [[FA WSL]] application,<ref name=ooh/> but in 2014 Trew controversially moved the club to Nottingham and rebranded it [[Notts County Ladies F.C.|Notts County Ladies]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-22335404|title=Lincoln Ladies move is 'own goal'|date=2013-04-29|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23375268|title=Lincoln Ladies defend Notts County relocation|date=2013-07-19|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Notts County==\nTrew purchased Notts County for [[\u00a3]]1 in February 2010 following the departure of [[Qadbak Investments]]. He inherited liabilities of \u00a37m from the former owners.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/sven-too-good-to-be-true-but-notts-county-are-having-the-last-laugh-2102546.html|title=Sven 'too good to be true' but Notts County are having the last laugh|author=Jon Culley|publisher=The Independent|date=10 October 2010|accessdate=18 January 2011|location=London}}</ref> On 25 February 2016, Trew stepped down as chairman of Notts County and announced that the club was for sale,<ref>http://www.nottinghampost.com/Ray-Trew-steps-chairman-Notts-County-puts-club/story-28807809-detail/story.html{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35659566|title=Notts County for sale as chairman Ray Trew quits|date=2016-02-25|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-gb}}</ref> but on 10 September 2016, Trew announced he had reinstated himself as chairman of Notts County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BBCRNS/status/774649122141958145|title=Ray Trew confirms to Colin Slater that he is back as Chairman of #notts. Slater: \"nothing immiment\" on sale of club. It remains for sale|last=BBC Nottingham Sport|first=|date=2016-09-10|website=Twitter.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On 12 January 2017, Trew sold the club to local businessman Alan Hardy, <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38583229|title=Notts County: Alan Hardy completes takeover from Ray Trew|date=2017-01-11|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-gb}}</ref> but one of Trew's companies named Pinnacle Advantage was owed a substantial sum of money by the club. This threatened to force the club into liquidation until an agreement was reached in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/central/2017-05-24/notts-county-liquidation-threat-lifted-after-dramatic-compromise/|title=Notts County liquidation threat lifted after 'dramatic compromise'|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Nottingham Rugby Club==\nIn July 2010 Trew took control of Nottingham Rugby Club, via Meadow Lane plc.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ray Trew takes over Nottingham Rugby Club |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/notts_county/8871338.stm|date=30 July 2010 | work=BBC News}}</ref> On 28 September 2011 Trew relinquished his interest in Nottingham Rugby Club.<ref>http://www.nottscountyfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10426~2465421,00.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trew, Ray}}\n[[Category:English football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name= Ray Trew\n|image=\n|caption=\n|image_size=\n|birth_name=Ray Trew\n|birth_date=\n|birth_place=[[England]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|occupation=[[Businessperson|Businessman]]\n|known= Owner of<br />''Contracting Solutions Group'' \n|spouse = \n|children=\n}}\n'''Raymond Arthur Trew''' (born December 1954)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/h8xK01UWHMbkqW_DxKzFZWVIBzo/appointments|title=Raymond Arthur TREW - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> is a [[Businessperson|businessman]] and former football club [[Chairman (official)|chairman]] from [[Lincolnshire]]. He is a former board member of [[Lincoln City F.C.]], [[Notts County F.C.]], and [[Notts County Ladies F.C.]].\n\nTrew achieved his wealth through [[recruitment]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/paulfletcher/2010/12/can_paul_ince_cut_it_at_notts.html#279512|title=Can Paul Ince cut it at Notts County?|author=Paul Fletcher|publisher=BBC Sport|date=11 December 2010|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref> having founded Contracting Solutions Group in 1995.<ref name=lorien>{{cite web|url=http://www.lorienresourcing.co.uk/about-us/management/6-ray-trew/default.aspx|title=the team: Ray Trew|publisher=Lorien Resourcing|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref> The company posted a \u00a33.7m profit in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/fasttrack/leagues/dbDetails.asp?siteID=5&compID=2967&yr=2010|title=Rank: 124   Contracting Solutions Group|publisher=Fasttrack|accessdate=18 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316172751/http://www.fasttrack.co.uk/fasttrack/leagues/dbDetails.asp?siteID=5&compID=2967&yr=2010|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Trew also maintains numerous other [[Privately held company|private companies]],<ref name=\":0\" /> though in 2019 his application for a gangmaster's license was turned down on the grounds that his previous business conduct was not 'fit and proper'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/news/local-news/former-notts-county-owner-ray-3077195|title=Ex-Notts owner Ray Trew's conduct 'extremely concerning' as he is denied licence|last=Whitfield|first=David|date=2019-07-10|website=nottinghampost|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/news/local-news/former-imps-director-refused-licence-3076882|title=Former Imps director labelled 'not fit and proper' by officials|last=Hennessy|first=Peter|date=2019-07-10|website=lincolnshirelive|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Lincoln City==\nOn 5 August 2003, Trew became an Associate Director at [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10440~406690,00.html\n|title=New Associate Director Comes On Board\n|date=5 August 2003\n|publisher=Lincoln City F.C. Official Website\n|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> becoming a full director at the end of the month.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10440~416709,00.html\n|title=Ray Becomes A 'Trew' Director\n|date=27 August 2003\n|publisher=Lincoln City F.C. Official Website\n|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> In August 2005 he was appointed Chairman of Football with Steff Wright succeeding Rob Bradley as Chairman of the Board.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10440~752929,00.html\n|title=Former Chairman Played \"A Massive Part\"\n|date=9 December 2005\n|publisher=Lincoln City F.C. Official Website\n|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> He departed in January 2006 after a boardroom dispute which saw manager [[Keith Alexander (footballer)|Keith Alexander]] placed on gardening leave, then re-instated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2330675/Lincolns-version-of-Big-Brother-starts-to-spin-out-of-control.html|title=Lincoln's version of Big Brother starts to spin out of control|publisher=The Telegraph|date=16 January 2006|accessdate=18 January 2011|author=Simon Goodley|location=London}}</ref> In April three of Trew's companies then terminated their sponsorship deals with the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/lincolnshire/4921702.stm|title=Imps on lookout for new sponsors |publisher=BBC|date=19 April 2006|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent bid to buy the club and provide substantial investment was blocked by the Lincoln City board, with chairman Steff Wright publicly questioning Trew's motives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twohundredpercent.net/?p=4500|title=The morning after the night before|publisher=Two hundred percent|date=11 February 2010|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/lincoln_city/5238016.stm|title=Lincoln chairman wary of takeover|publisher=BBC|date=2 August 2006|accessdate=18 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Lincoln Ladies==\nIn 2006 Trew joined the committee of [[Lincoln Ladies F.C.|Lincoln City Ladies]]. In addition to an \u00a38,000-per-season sponsorship through his SportsTV company, Trew provided additional backing of up to \u00a310,000 to aid the club's promotion bid.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/nov/06/womensfootball.sport|title=Lincoln's original imps still set for the top despite cup defeat|author=Tony Leighton|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 November 2006|accessdate=18 January 2011|location=London}}</ref> In 2008 the club changed its name to OOH Lincoln Ladies, due to a sponsorship deal with Trew's Out Of Home marketing company.<ref name=ooh>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/nov/30/lincoln-women-football-super-league|title=OOH Lincoln declare intention to join women's Super League in 2011|author=Tony Leighton|publisher=The Guardian|date=30 November 2009|accessdate=18 January 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nTrew also backed the club's successful [[FA WSL]] application,<ref name=ooh/> but in 2014 Trew controversially moved the club to Nottingham and rebranded it [[Notts County Ladies F.C.|Notts County Ladies]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-22335404|title=Lincoln Ladies move is 'own goal'|date=2013-04-29|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/23375268|title=Lincoln Ladies defend Notts County relocation|date=2013-07-19|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Notts County==\nTrew purchased Notts County for [[\u00a3]]1 in February 2010 following the departure of [[Qadbak Investments]]. He inherited liabilities of \u00a37m from the former owners.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/sven-too-good-to-be-true-but-notts-county-are-having-the-last-laugh-2102546.html|title=Sven 'too good to be true' but Notts County are having the last laugh|author=Jon Culley|publisher=The Independent|date=10 October 2010|accessdate=18 January 2011|location=London}}</ref> On 25 February 2016, Trew stepped down as chairman of Notts County and announced that the club was for sale<ref>http://www.nottinghampost.com/Ray-Trew-steps-chairman-Notts-County-puts-club/story-28807809-detail/story.html{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35659566|title=Notts County for sale as chairman Ray Trew quits|date=2016-02-25|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-gb}}</ref>, but on 10 September 2016, Trew announced he had reinstated himself as chairman of Notts County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BBCRNS/status/774649122141958145|title=Ray Trew confirms to Colin Slater that he is back as Chairman of #notts. Slater: \"nothing immiment\" on sale of club. It remains for sale|last=BBC Nottingham Sport|first=|date=2016-09-10|website=Twitter.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> On 12 January 2017, Trew sold the club to local businessman Alan Hardy, <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38583229|title=Notts County: Alan Hardy completes takeover from Ray Trew|date=2017-01-11|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-22|language=en-gb}}</ref> but one of Trew's companies named Pinnacle Advantage was owed a substantial sum of money by the club. This threatened to force the club into liquidation until an agreement was reached in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/central/2017-05-24/notts-county-liquidation-threat-lifted-after-dramatic-compromise/|title=Notts County liquidation threat lifted after 'dramatic compromise'|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Nottingham Rugby Club==\nIn July 2010 Trew took control of Nottingham Rugby Club, via Meadow Lane plc.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ray Trew takes over Nottingham Rugby Club |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/notts_county/8871338.stm|date=30 July 2010 | work=BBC News}}</ref> On 28 September 2011 Trew relinquished his interest in Nottingham Rugby Club.<ref>http://www.nottscountyfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10426~2465421,00.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trew, Ray}}\n[[Category:English football chairmen and investors]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Palmiped", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotts County:ref after punctuation as per MoS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Trew"}
{"title_page": "Carolyn Goodman (politician)", "text_new": "{{About|the mayor of Las Vegas, Nevada|the clinical psychologist|Carolyn Goodman (psychologist)}}\n{{short description|American politician from Nevada}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Carolyn Goodman\n|image       = Carolyn Goodman (1).jpg\n|office      = 22nd [[List of mayors of Las Vegas|Mayor of Las Vegas]]\n|term_start  = July 6, 2011\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Oscar Goodman]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Carolyn Goldmark\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1939|3|25}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2009\u2013present)\n|otherparty  = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (1985\u20132009)\n|spouse      = {{Marriage|[[Oscar Goodman]]|1962}}\n|children    = 4, including [[Ross Goodman|Ross]]\n|education   = [[Bryn Mawr College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])\n}}\n\n'''Carolyn Goodman''' ([[n\u00e9e]] '''Goldmark'''; born March 25, 1939<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?rank=1&new=1&MSAV=1&msT=1&gss=angs-c&gsfn=Carolyn+g&gsln=Goodman&gsln_x=XO&cpxt=0&uidh=381&cp=0&pcat=DIR_TELEPHONE&h=120323827&db=USpublicrecords3&indiv=1&ml_rpos=12|title=U.S. Public Records Index, Volume 1 about Carolyn G Goodman|publisher=Ancestry.com|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref>) is an American [[politician]] serving [[mayor]] of [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]] since 2011.<ref name=\"lasvegassun\">{{Cite news|title=Carolyn Goodman easily wins race for Las Vegas mayor|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/jun/07/carolyn-goodman-wins-race-las-vegas-mayor|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]|first=Delen|last=Goldberg|date=June 7, 2011|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> She is the second female mayor of Las Vegas, after [[Jan Laverty Jones]], and the wife of former mayor and attorney [[Oscar Goodman]].<ref name=\"lasvegassun\"/>\n\n==Education==\nGoodman earned a bachelor's degree in anthropology from [[Bryn Mawr College]] in 1961.<ref>[http://bulletin.brynmawr.edu/features/qa-with-mayor-carolyn-goodman Profile], brynmawr.edu; accessed May 22, 2015.</ref> Carolyn and Oscar Goodman moved to Las Vegas from Philadelphia in 1964.<ref>[http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/Mayor_Carolyn_Goodman_approved_bio_July_2011.pdf Profile] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027101042/http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/Mayor_Carolyn_Goodman_approved_bio_July_2011.pdf |date=October 27, 2011 }}, lasvegasnevada.gov; accessed May 22, 2015.</ref> She graduated from the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] in 1973 with a master's degree in counseling.<ref>[http://education.unlv.edu/alumni/application.html University of Nevada alumni]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, education.unlv.edu; accessed May 22, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Career ==\nGoodman is the founder, president and trustee emeritus of [[The Meadows School]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.themeadowsschool.org/res/Documents/About_Us/Strategic_Plan.pdf |title= Strategic Plan |work= The Meadows School |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111002023025/http://www.themeadowsschool.org/res/Documents/About_Us/Strategic_Plan.pdf |archivedate= October 2, 2011 |accessdate= May 22, 2015 }}</ref>  Goodman and her husband moved to Las Vegas in 1964 and soon became active in the local Jewish federation.<ref name=ajewishgoodman /> Eventually, she became the leader of the local Jewish federation's women's division, a position she held for several years.<ref name=ajewishgoodman>https://www.jta.org/2016/02/23/news-opinion/united-states/las-vegas-jewish-mayor-talks-about-her-city-how-husband-would-love-to-run-against-trump</ref>  She received the 2009 Commitment to Education award from the [[United Way of America|United Way]] of Southern Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uwsn.org/sup.php?id=486|title=2009 Commitment to Education award|work=United Way of Southern Nevada|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201164543/http://www.uwsn.org/sup.php?id=486|archivedate=December 1, 2010|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn [[2011 Las Vegas mayoral election|June 7, 2011]], she was elected Mayor of Las Vegas with 60 percent of the vote; she assumed office on July 6, 2011.<ref name=\"lasvegassun\" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/CERTIFIED_CANDIDATE_LIST_2011__FORM_.pdf |title= Certified Candidate List 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110703051428/http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/CERTIFIED_CANDIDATE_LIST_2011__FORM_.pdf |date= 2011 |archivedate= July 3, 2011 |work= City of Las Vegas |accessdate = May 22, 2015 }}</ref> She was first re-elected [[2015 Las Vegas mayoral election|in 2015]], and [[2019 Las Vegas mayoral election|in April 2019]] was re-elected again to a third (and, due to term limits, final) term, winning 83.5 percent of the vote to avoid a runoff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/apr/02/carolyn-goodman-wins-her-third-and-final-term-as-l/|title=Carolyn Goodman wins her third and final term as Las Vegas mayor|work=Las Vegas Sun|last=Wilson|first=Miranda|date=April 2, 2019|location=Las Vegas, Nevada|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>.\n\nOn October 24, 2011, Goodman greeted [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] at [[McCarran International Airport]]. In regard to negative remarks President Obama made about Las Vegas two years earlier that had angered Goodman's husband Oscar, the previous mayor, she told Obama that \"the slate is brand new and clean\", and gave him one of her lucky mayor chips as a gift.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ktnv.com/news/local/132503373.html |title= Meeting with President Obama |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120404130625/http://www.ktnv.com/news/local/132503373.html |archivedate= April 4, 2012 |date=April 4, 2012 |work= [[KTNV-TV|KTNV]] |accessdate= May 22, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2015, Goodman endorsed [[Ruben Kihuen]] for the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Nevada, 2016|2016]]. Kihuen defeated incumbent U.S. Representative [[Cresent Hardy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://lasvegas.cbslocal.com/2015/07/20/mayor-carolyn-goodman-endorses-heck-for-senate/|title=Mayor Carolyn Goodman Endorses Joe Heck For Senate|date=July 20, 2015|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[KXNT (AM)]]|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> Days later, she endorsed [[Joe Heck]] for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in [[United States Senate election in Nevada, 2016|2016]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/jul/20/las-vegas-mayor-carolyn-goodman-endorses-joe-heck-/|title=Las Vegas Mayor Carolyn Goodman endorses Joe Heck for Senate|date=July 20, 2015|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> On August 3, 2016, Goodman declined to endorse [[Hillary Clinton]] or [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Morell|first=Casey|url=https://knpr.org/headline/2016-08/carolyn-goodman-rules-out-endorsing-clinton-or-trump|title=Carolyn Goodman Rules Out Endorsing Clinton or Trump|date=August 3, 2016|publisher=[[KNPR]]|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> Goodman identifies as an [[independent politician|independent]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Levine |first1=Daniel S. |title=Carolyn Goodman: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/news/2017/10/carolyn-goodman-las-vegas-mayor-shooting-response-husband/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=26 November 2019 |language=en |date=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring her tenure as mayor, Goodman tried to promote Las Vegas as a home for professional sports teams. The [[Vegas Golden Knights]] began playing professional hockey in the 2017-2018 season and the [[Oakland Raiders]] announced their relocation to Las Vegas beginning in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brewer |first=Ray |date=February 12, 2018 |title=Carolyn Goodman was right \u2014 Las Vegas is a great spot for major league sports |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2018/feb/12/carolyn-goodman-was-right-las-vegas-is-a-great-spo/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref> Goodman attempted to lure a soccer team to Las Vegas several times, including bids for a [[Major League Soccer]] expansion team, and ultimately got a second-division team, the [[Las Vegas Lights FC]] of the [[United Soccer League]], which began playing in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Munks |first=Jamie |date=August 9, 2017 |title=Dignitaries to make announcement about Las Vegas soccer team |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/dignitaries-to-make-announcement-about-las-vegas-soccer-team/ |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGoodman is not eligible to run for re-election in 2024 due to [[Term limits in the United States|term limits]].<ref>https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/2019-legislature/nevada-sees-many-new-laws-but-how-will-they-affect-you-1682418/</ref><ref>https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/jun/25/new-local-election-law-shifts-term-lengths-cuts-co/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGoodman's husband is Oscar Goodman. They have four children (including [[Ross Goodman|Ross]]) and six grandchildren.<ref>[http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/BIO_for_Mayor_Goodman.pdf Carolyn Goodman biodata] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222163929/http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/BIO_for_Mayor_Goodman.pdf |date=December 22, 2014 }}, lasvegasnevada.gov; accessed May 22, 2015.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of mayors of the 50 largest cities in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|Carolyn Goodman 02}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Oscar Goodman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Las Vegas, Nevada|Mayor of Las Vegas]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Nevada cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Mayors of the 50 largest U.S. cities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goodman, Carolyn G.}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:Bryn Mawr College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:Nevada Democrats]]\n[[Category:Nevada Independents]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:First Ladies and Gentlemen of Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Las Vegas alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in Nevada politics]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in Nevada]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the mayor of Las Vegas, Nevada|the clinical psychologist|Carolyn Goodman (psychologist)}}\n{{short description|American politician from Nevada}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Carolyn Goodman\n|image       = Carolyn Goodman (1).jpg\n|office      = 22nd [[List of mayors of Las Vegas|Mayor of Las Vegas]]\n|term_start  = July 6, 2011\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Oscar Goodman]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Carolyn Goldmark\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1939|3|25}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2009\u2013present)\n|otherparty  = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (1985\u20132009)\n|spouse      = {{Marriage|[[Oscar Goodman]]|1962}}\n|children    = 4, including [[Ross Goodman|Ross]]\n|education   = [[Bryn Mawr College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])\n}}\n\n'''Carolyn Goodman''' ([[n\u00e9e]] '''Goldmark'''; born March 25, 1939<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?rank=1&new=1&MSAV=1&msT=1&gss=angs-c&gsfn=Carolyn+g&gsln=Goodman&gsln_x=XO&cpxt=0&uidh=381&cp=0&pcat=DIR_TELEPHONE&h=120323827&db=USpublicrecords3&indiv=1&ml_rpos=12|title=U.S. Public Records Index, Volume 1 about Carolyn G Goodman|publisher=Ancestry.com|accessdate=21 December 2013}}</ref>) is an American [[politician]] serving [[mayor]] of [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]] since 2011.<ref name=\"lasvegassun\">{{Cite news|title=Carolyn Goodman easily wins race for Las Vegas mayor|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/jun/07/carolyn-goodman-wins-race-las-vegas-mayor|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]|first=Delen|last=Goldberg|date=June 7, 2011|accessdate=June 13, 2011}}</ref> She is the second female mayor of Las Vegas, after [[Jan Laverty Jones]], and the wife of former mayor and attorney [[Oscar Goodman]].<ref name=\"lasvegassun\"/>\n\n==Education==\nGoodman earned a bachelor's degree in anthropology from [[Bryn Mawr College]] in 1961.<ref>[http://bulletin.brynmawr.edu/features/qa-with-mayor-carolyn-goodman Profile], brynmawr.edu; accessed May 22, 2015.</ref> Carolyn and Oscar Goodman moved to Las Vegas from Philadelphia in 1964.<ref>[http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/Mayor_Carolyn_Goodman_approved_bio_July_2011.pdf Profile] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027101042/http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/Mayor_Carolyn_Goodman_approved_bio_July_2011.pdf |date=October 27, 2011 }}, lasvegasnevada.gov; accessed May 22, 2015.</ref> She graduated from the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] in 1973 with a master's degree in counseling.<ref>[http://education.unlv.edu/alumni/application.html University of Nevada alumni]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, education.unlv.edu; accessed May 22, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Career ==\nGoodman is the founder, president and trustee emeritus of [[The Meadows School]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.themeadowsschool.org/res/Documents/About_Us/Strategic_Plan.pdf |title= Strategic Plan |work= The Meadows School |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111002023025/http://www.themeadowsschool.org/res/Documents/About_Us/Strategic_Plan.pdf |archivedate= October 2, 2011 |accessdate= May 22, 2015 }}</ref>  Goodman and her husband moved to Las Vegas in 1964 and soon became active in the local Jewish federation.<ref name=ajewishgoodman /> Eventually, she became the leader of the local Jewish federation's women's division, a position she held for several years.<ref name=ajewishgoodman>https://www.jta.org/2016/02/23/news-opinion/united-states/las-vegas-jewish-mayor-talks-about-her-city-how-husband-would-love-to-run-against-trump</ref>  She received the 2009 Commitment to Education award from the [[United Way of America|United Way]] of Southern Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uwsn.org/sup.php?id=486|title=2009 Commitment to Education award|work=United Way of Southern Nevada|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201164543/http://www.uwsn.org/sup.php?id=486|archivedate=December 1, 2010|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn [[2011 Las Vegas mayoral election|June 7, 2011]], she was elected Mayor of Las Vegas with 60 percent of the vote; she assumed office on July 6, 2011.<ref name=\"lasvegassun\" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/CERTIFIED_CANDIDATE_LIST_2011__FORM_.pdf |title= Certified Candidate List 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110703051428/http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/CERTIFIED_CANDIDATE_LIST_2011__FORM_.pdf |date= 2011 |archivedate= July 3, 2011 |work= City of Las Vegas |accessdate = May 22, 2015 }}</ref> She was first re-elected [[2015 Las Vegas mayoral election|in 2015]], and [[2019 Las Vegas mayoral election|in April 2019]] was re-elected again to a third (and, due to term limits, final) term, winning 83.5 percent of the vote to avoid a runoff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/apr/02/carolyn-goodman-wins-her-third-and-final-term-as-l/|title=Carolyn Goodman wins her third and final term as Las Vegas mayor|work=Las Vegas Sun|last=Wilson|first=Miranda|date=April 2, 2019|location=Las Vegas, Nevada|access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>.\n\nOn October 24, 2011, Goodman greeted [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] at [[McCarran International Airport]]. In regard to negative remarks President Obama made about Las Vegas two years earlier that had angered Goodman's husband Oscar, the previous mayor, she told Obama that \"the slate is brand new and clean\", and gave him one of her lucky mayor chips as a gift.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ktnv.com/news/local/132503373.html |title= Meeting with President Obama |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120404130625/http://www.ktnv.com/news/local/132503373.html |archivedate= April 4, 2012 |date=April 4, 2012 |work= [[KTNV-TV|KTNV]] |accessdate= May 22, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2015, Goodman endorsed [[Ruben Kihuen]] for the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Nevada, 2016|2016]]. Kihuen defeated incumbent U.S. Representative [[Cresent Hardy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://lasvegas.cbslocal.com/2015/07/20/mayor-carolyn-goodman-endorses-heck-for-senate/|title=Mayor Carolyn Goodman Endorses Joe Heck For Senate|date=July 20, 2015|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[KXNT (AM)]]|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> Days later, she endorsed [[Joe Heck]] for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in [[United States Senate election in Nevada, 2016|2016]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/jul/20/las-vegas-mayor-carolyn-goodman-endorses-joe-heck-/|title=Las Vegas Mayor Carolyn Goodman endorses Joe Heck for Senate|date=July 20, 2015|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[Las Vegas Sun]]|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> On August 3, 2016, Goodman declined to endorse [[Hillary Clinton]] or [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Morell|first=Casey|url=https://knpr.org/headline/2016-08/carolyn-goodman-rules-out-endorsing-clinton-or-trump|title=Carolyn Goodman Rules Out Endorsing Clinton or Trump|date=August 3, 2016|publisher=[[KNPR]]|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> Goodman identifies as an [[independent politician|independent]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Levine |first1=Daniel S. |title=Carolyn Goodman: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/news/2017/10/carolyn-goodman-las-vegas-mayor-shooting-response-husband/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=26 November 2019 |language=en |date=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring her tenure as mayor, Goodman tried to promote Las Vegas as a home for professional sports teams. The [[Vegas Golden Knights]] began playing professional hockey in the 2017-2018 season and the [[Oakland Raiders]] announced their relocation to Las Vegas beginning in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brewer |first=Ray |date=February 12, 2018 |title=Carolyn Goodman was right \u2014 Las Vegas is a great spot for major league sports |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2018/feb/12/carolyn-goodman-was-right-las-vegas-is-a-great-spo/ |work=Las Vegas Sun |accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref> Goodman attempted to lure a soccer team to Las Vegas several times, including bids for a [[Major League Soccer]] expansion team, and ultimately got a second-division team, the [[Las Vegas Lights FC]] of the [[United Soccer League]], which began playing in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Munks |first=Jamie |date=August 9, 2017 |title=Dignitaries to make announcement about Las Vegas soccer team |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/dignitaries-to-make-announcement-about-las-vegas-soccer-team/ |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGoodman is not eligible to run for re-election in 2024 due to [[Term limits in the United States|term limits]].<ref>https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/2019-legislature/nevada-sees-many-new-laws-but-how-will-they-affect-you-1682418/</ref><ref>https://lasvegassun.com/news/2019/jun/25/new-local-election-law-shifts-term-lengths-cuts-co/</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2020, during the [[covid-19]] pandemic, Goodman questioned the impact of [[social distancing]] in an interview with [[Anderson Cooper]]. She said \"We [referring to the city] offered to be a control group\" to test what would happen if casinos reopened, but said that the offer had been \"turned down\" by \"our statistician.\" She went on to suggest that social distancing should be subjected to a placebo test, adding \"We would love to be that placebo.\" When Cooper asked if she would be on the casino floors with the workers who would be at risk in such an experiment, she appeared to avoid the question. When pressed by Cooper, she asked what purpose that would serve, and said that she had a family. <ref>https://twitter.com/timjhogan/status/1253051630758625281</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGoodman's husband is Oscar Goodman. They have four children (including [[Ross Goodman|Ross]]) and six grandchildren.<ref>[http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/BIO_for_Mayor_Goodman.pdf Carolyn Goodman biodata] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222163929/http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/files/BIO_for_Mayor_Goodman.pdf |date=December 22, 2014 }}, lasvegasnevada.gov; accessed May 22, 2015.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of mayors of the 50 largest cities in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|Carolyn Goodman 02}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Oscar Goodman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Las Vegas, Nevada|Mayor of Las Vegas]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Nevada cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Mayors of the 50 largest U.S. cities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goodman, Carolyn G.}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:Bryn Mawr College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:Nevada Democrats]]\n[[Category:Nevada Independents]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:First Ladies and Gentlemen of Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Las Vegas alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in Nevada politics]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in Nevada]]\n", "name_user": "NedFausa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Encyclopedic content must be verifiable \u2013 this tweet is notWP:RS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carolyn_Goodman_(politician)"}
